<page_title>Solving molecular structures from molecular crystals: X-ray crystallography</page_title>
<text>Solving molecular structures from molecular crystals: X-ray crystallography
p.  6 of 7

&lt; Previous | Index l Next&gt;

There is currently no technology available that enables us to easily manipulate a single molecule to get its imagery.The signal from a single molecule is just too weak to detect. The solution to this problem is to crystallize the molecules from a solution and carry out X-ray diffraction on the crystal. The question then becomes: Is the diffraction pattern of a whole crystal the same as that of a single molecule, or can it be reduced to that of a single molecule? The following experiment investigates this. 

  
   

Follow these steps: 

(a) Click the top button on the X-ray diffraction instrument to produce an X-ray image for the molecular crystal shown above, and then hit the button on the X-ray control panel with a camera icon to take a snapshot of the X-ray image; press the magnifying glass a few times. 

(b) Select the &quot;Single Molecule&quot; button and repeat (a). 

(c) Go up and down the scale with the positive and negative magnifiers, and look for correspondences. Take snapshots with the camera icon on the defraction tool, when you feel the images are closest.  

